# DedgeAuth Auth & Navigation Diagnostics — Auto-Run Protocol

## When This Rule Triggers

Run `scripts\Get-DedgeAuthDiagnostics.ps1` **immediately** (before any manual investigation) when the user reports ANY of these symptoms:

- App links on login page don't work / redirect back to login
- "401 Unauthorized" on `/api/auth/refresh`, `/api/auth/me`, or `/api/auth/create-code`
- Login page shows but user cannot reach consumer apps
- Auth code exchange fails
- Redirect loop between DedgeAuth and consumer app
- "Authenticating with Windows..." hangs
- User says "I can't get to [app]" or "it just reloads the login page"
- Browser console shows 401s on DedgeAuth endpoints
- Silent re-authentication fails

## How to Run

```powershell
# Against the test server (default)
pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "c:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\scripts\Get-DedgeAuthDiagnostics.ps1" -BaseUrl http://dedge-server -ServerName dedge-server

# Against localhost (local dev)
pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "c:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\scripts\Get-DedgeAuthDiagnostics.ps1" -BaseUrl http://localhost

# Custom output path
pwsh.exe -NoProfile -File "c:\opt\src\DedgeAuth\scripts\Get-DedgeAuthDiagnostics.ps1" -OutputPath "C:\temp\diag.md"
```

The script writes a full markdown report to `$env:TEMP\DedgeAuth-Diagnostics.md` and prints it to stdout. **Read the report before making any changes.**

## What the Script Collects (10 sections)

| Section | What it checks |
|---|---|
| 1. Server logs | Last 60 lines of DedgeAuth.Api log (local + server), error/warning counts |
| 2. Deployed file versions | DLL versions and timestamps across staging share, IIS install, and local |
| 3. API endpoint health | Health, Scalar, login, me, apps, apps/tree, redirect, validate |
| 4. Auth flow E2E | login → create-code → consumer app code exchange for all 5 apps |
| 5. Refresh token cookies | Set-Cookie headers: Path, SameSite, HttpOnly attributes |
| 6. Database state | Apps list via API (appId, baseUrl, active status) |
| 7. IIS app pool state | Pool status, runtime, identity (or netstat on dev machine) |
| 8. login.html functions | Checks for openApp, storeAccessToken, create-code, redirect fallback, same-tab nav |
| 9. Staging vs IIS comparison | File timestamps between staging share and IIS install path — detects stale deploys |
| 10. Summary | Actionable recommendations based on findings |

## Decision Tree After Reading the Report

```
Report shows STALE files in section 9?
  → Run: IIS-DeployApp.ps1 -SiteName DedgeAuth
  → Then re-run diagnostics to confirm

Report shows login.html missing openApp() in section 8?
  → login.html on server is outdated
  → Run: Build-And-Publish.ps1 then IIS-DeployApp.ps1

Report shows create-code returns 401 in section 4?
  → JWT is expired or invalid
  → Check AccessTokenExpirationMinutes in appsettings.json
  → Check if login actually returns a valid JWT (section 3)

Report shows cookie Path is NOT /DedgeAuth in section 5?
  → SetRefreshTokenCookie in AuthController.cs is missing Path
  → Fix: Path = Request.PathBase.Value

Report shows consumer app code exchange fails in section 4c?
  → The consumer app's DedgeAuth.Client middleware may be outdated
  → Rebuild consumer app: Build-And-Publish-ALL.ps1

Report shows redirect endpoint returns 302 to login in section 3?
  → No valid cookies available — expected for unauthenticated probe
  → If cookies ARE being sent and it still redirects: check AuthController.RedirectWithCode

All sections green but user still can't navigate?
  → Browser-specific issue (popup blocker, third-party cookie policy)
  → Test with browser_navigate in Cursor IDE browser
  → Check browser console for JavaScript errors
```

## Key Auth Flow Reference

```
User clicks app link on DedgeAuth login page
    │
    ▼
openApp() in login.html
    │
    ├─ JWT in localStorage → POST /api/auth/create-code
    │   ├─ 200 → navigate same tab: AppUrl?code=CODE
    │   └─ 401 → fallback below
    │
    └─ No JWT or fallback → GET /api/auth/redirect?returnUrl=AppUrl
        ├─ Has DedgeAuth_jwt cookie → create code, 302 to AppUrl?code=CODE
        ├─ Has refreshToken cookie → validate, create code, 302
        └─ No auth → 302 to /DedgeAuth/login.html?returnUrl=AppUrl

Consumer app receives ?code=CODE
    │
    ▼
DedgeAuthTokenExtractionMiddleware
    │
    └─ POST /api/auth/exchange (server-to-server)
        ├─ 200 → Set DedgeAuth_access_token cookie, 302 to clean URL
        └─ 401 → code expired/used, redirect to login
```

## Critical Files

| File | Purpose |
|---|---|
| `AuthController.cs` | Login, create-code, redirect, exchange, refresh, me endpoints |
| `AuthService.cs` | Token generation, refresh token rotation, ValidateRefreshTokenUserAsync |
| `login.html` | openApp(), storeAccessToken(), tryLocalTokenRedirect(), tryAutoKerberos() |
| `DedgeAuthTokenExtractionMiddleware.cs` | Consumer-side: extracts ?code= and exchanges server-to-server |
| `DedgeAuthRedirectMiddleware.cs` | Consumer-side: redirects unauthenticated to DedgeAuth login |
| `DedgeAuthSessionValidationMiddleware.cs` | Consumer-side: validates session, records visits |

## Do NOT Skip This

If the user reports an auth/navigation issue, **always run the diagnostic script first**. The report takes ~15 seconds and prevents hours of manual investigation. Read the entire report before touching any code.